        <h1>
            Two structurally useful moral principles and their correlation with the value of reason
            and the limit of light speed
            </h1>
        <p><cite>
            Michael Allan.<sup class='ref'>[<a href='#MCA' id='MCA-a'>MCA</a>]</sup>  2014-2016…
            Two structurally useful moral principles and their correlation with the value of reason
            and the limit of light speed.  Web draft.
            <a href='https://github.com/Michael-Allan/100-0/tree/master/poll/c/pipe/100-5/norm.xht'
                    >https://github.com/Michael-Allan/100-0/tree/master/poll/c/pipe/100-5/norm.xht</a
                    > <sup class='ref'>[<a href='#H' id='H-a'>H</a>]</sup>
            </cite></p>
        <blockquote>
            Then the Universe is water; water without end or beginning;
            without Earth or sky; without space or light; without sound or movement.
            Then the dark waters lie still and silent and waiting, touching nothing.<br/>
            <i>What shape shall I take to rescue the Earth from this flood?</i>
            <footer>
                — <cite>Buck,
                Mahabharata <sup class='ref'>[<a href='#Buc73' id='Buc73p165'>Buc73</a>]</sup></cite>
                </footer>
            </blockquote>
        <!-- <<< -->

<section>
    <p>
        The principles are:
        </p>
    <dl>
        <dt><dfn>M1</dfn></dt>
        <dd>Relate personal action to an ultimate end</dd>
        <dt><dfn>M2</dfn></dt>
        <dd>Promote a maximum, universal sum of personal freedom</dd>
        </dl>
    <p>
        For my part, I take these two principles to be sufficient for moral judgement.
        Whatever obeys them, I judge to be right; whatever counters them, wrong.
        Right (viz. what ought to be) consists in obedience to both principles together,
        while wrong consists in countering either, or both.
        That which neither obeys nor counters, I judge to be neither right nor wrong.
        </p>
    <p>
        But I will not advance a general claim of completeness here.<sup class='ref'>[<a href='#SC' id='SC-a'>SC</a>]</sup>
        Here I intend only to convince you that M1 and M2 are well fitted to their postulates
        and useful for structural purposes.  People can build sturdy things with them.
        </p>
    <p>
        The postulates are:
        </p>
    <dl>
        <dt><dfn>P1</dfn></dt>
        <dd>I value reason the most</dd>
        </dl>
    <dl>
        <dt><dfn>P2</dfn></dt>
        <dd>I think that all communications are limited to light speed</dd>
        </dl>
    <p>
         Even the most urgent of news cannot travel very quickly through the stars.
         But sometimes a limitation is a good thing, especially in human affairs.
         The philosopher and historian of ideas, Isaiah Berlin, who was much concerned
         with political ethics and the danger of violence in pursuing collective ends,
         once recommended that the best we might hope for is some kind of limiting arrangement
         that served to protect “differing groups of human beings — at the very least to prevent them
         from attempting to exterminate each other, and, so far as possible, to prevent them
         from hurting each other”.<sup class='ref'>[<a href='#Ber78' id='Ber78p50'>Ber78</a>]</sup>
        </p>
    <p>
        …
        A grand-scale version of this safeguard is already offered in the limit of light speed.
        …
        </p>
    <dl>
        <dt><dfn>M0</dfn></dt>
        <dd>
            I desire the endless continuity of rational being
            that is made feasible by the limit of light speed
            </dd>
        </dl>
    <p>
        History gave me M2.  I could almost write it down verbatim:
        </p>
    <table border='1'>
        <caption>Correlation of principles.</caption>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td>form</td>
                <td>M2</td>
                <td>Promote a maximum, universal sum of personal freedom</td>
                    <!--
                    ( a maximum of personal freedom compatible with equal freedoms in general
                        -->
                <td>means</td>
                </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>form</td>
                <td>M1</td>
                <td>Relate personal action to an ultimate end</td>
                <td>means</td>
                </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>matter</td>
                <td>M0</td>
                <td>
                    I desire the endless continuity of rational being
                    that is made feasible by the limit of light speed
                    </td>
                <td>end</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    <p>
        I could also get M1 from history if I were to analyze the religious, utopian tradition of my culture.
        In fact I got it by analyzing M0.  In either case, cutting away the particulars
        uncovers an M1-like form.<sup class='ref'>[<a href='#MF' id='MF-a'>MF</a>]</sup>
        Yet no inheritance from the past, nor faith, nor hope for the future,
        equips me to argue convincingly for these two principles
        without the material support of M0 and its unshakeable, physical foundation.
        Nor could I reliably interpret the “moral law within me” based on reason
        were it not also written in the “starry heavens above”.<sup class='ref'>[<a href='#KE' id='KE-a'>KE</a>]</sup>
        </p>
