                MF<a href=
              '#MF-a'>↑</a>
            </dt>
        <dd>
            These relations of matter and form were suggested by my reading of Kant’s <i>Groundwork</i>.
            “All rational cognition is either <i>material</i> and considers some object,
            or <i>formal</i> and occupied merely with the form of the understanding and of reason itself,
            and with the universal rules of thinking as such, regardless of differences among its objects.” <sup class='ref'>[<a href='#Kan4' id='Kan4q387'>Kan4</a>]</sup>
            </dd>
        <dt id='SC'>
                SC<a href=
              '#SC-a'>↑</a>
            </dt>
        <dd>
            I cannot see how to apply Kant’s moral principle “cleansed of everything empirical”
            except by reformulating it on empirical grounds (P1, P2).
            Nor can I see how to argue from those grounds purely by logic,
            so that here I introduce further elements from the world of experience.
            Yet I respect Kant’s opinion and wish to avoid “peddling the empirical mixed with the rational”.
            Therefore I restrict the scope of my claims for the result (M1, M2),
            which I present not as an absolute “moral law” for all possible universes,
            but as a fallible “practical rule” for this one.<sup class='ref'>[<a href='#Kan4' id='Kan4q388-9'>Kan4</a>]</sup>
            </dd>
        <dt id='WF'>
                WF<a href=
              '#WF-a'>↑</a>
            </dt>
        <dd>
            Kant asserts: “that we must necessarily lend to every rational being that has a will
            also the idea of freedom, under which alone it acts.” <sup class='ref'>[<a href='#Kan4' id='Kan4q448'>Kan4</a>]</sup>
            Note that here M1 correlates to ‘will’ and M2 the ‘idea of freedom’.
            </dd>
